Rating: 4
Because I'm one of those "crazy" types who first tries a recipe exactly as written, I can post a truly honest review of this recipe. And, after making it 5 years in a row, I can also post honestly about what has worked for me. First: the only part of this recipe I leave out is the instacure. Simply no need. Other than that, there is NO need to vary from ANY other part of the recipe--brining time, perfect. Do it the full 8 days, use the 1 1/2 cups of salt (it's required for the curing), and rinse the heck out of the brisket under VERY cold water. I essentially put a shallow pot in the sink and run the water for about 10 solid minutes. Yes, I'm wasting water, but I only make this the week before St. Patrick's Day each year, so I'll adjust my other spending for the month. Do use Harp Lager for the brine. Do use Guinness for the slow cooking. 8 lb. brisket for 10 hours on low in the crockpot is the best way to cook this, I know, I've done it all ways. The meat is still fork tender, but sliceable so it's not like shredded roast beef. Do make the Guinness Mustard. It's a MUST. If you can't fit the cabbage, carrots and onions in the crockpot, take some stock out of the pot, add it to a nice deep stockpot and put the veg on an hour before supper and they're perfectly done. Soda bread, scallion Champ (potatoes) and Irish Car Bomb cupcakes for dessert and you can make an Irish family truly happy. Each March, my husband's huge clans talks about this meal for WEEKS. My only problem is that so many folks are invited now, there aren't any leftovers...

Rating: 4
Made this year for St Paddy's and everyone raved. I only brined for 5 days total, and then put in a crockpot overnight, 1 hour on high, 7 on low. Kept it on warm the next day until we served for early supper. Incredibly tender. One tip is that for boiling the veggies in the stock that the meat cooked in, next time I would make sure to either use a gravy separator or put the stock in the fridge to solidify the fat, then remove. I did not pierce the meat either, nor use the insta-cure. Will definately make again.

