Rating: 4
I served this dish at a St. Patrick's Day party and it was a huge it. I bought two five-pound briskets in order to feed 11 people. I cooked one of the briskets in a slow cooker for about 12 hours and the other I cooked according to the recipe. Obviously the slow cooked brisket turned out much better. Also, I only brined for four days and I cut about a cup of salt out--the meat was not overly salty, and no one seems to have died from botulism yet. It might go without saying, but this is a lot of food to cook at one time, it's definitely worth mapping out ahead of time how you're going to accommodate the bulk of stuff in your kitchen, especially if you'll be entertaining and cooking at the same time.

Rating: 4
This was a hit! Used three 3 to 4 lb briskets from Costco to serve 11 adults. We could have squeezed by with two but there would not have been any leftovers. Brined in ziplock bags for 6 days. It was salty but what can you expect from brined meats? It didn't deter our guests from going back for seconds. Next time I might try 5 days. Cooked two in a crock pot for 8 hours on low with a full recipe of cooking liquid/spices. Delicious. Cooked the third on stove top for recommended time with half recipe of cooking liquid/spices. Also delicious. The horseradish sauce was amazing and a perfect compliment to the meat. The vegetables were incredible and I didn't find them to be overly greasy.

